        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>
We assume that the X-ray/CO(1-0) ratio is constant in the overall area of outflowing gas.
Therefore, we could estimate the rms level of CO(1-0) emission 
 to detect weak CO emission from the large scale X-ray outflow region.

Comparing the NMA CO(1-0) contour and  the CXO X-ray contour,
the distribution of molecular outflow roughly matches the northern X-ray outflow at contour level of 12 of the peak intensity.
Thus, if the molecular gas can be entrained to the northern X-ray outflow area with contour level of 4%,
 the CO(1-0) emission intensity in the same area
 should be 30% of the emission of the molecular outflow detected by the NMA.
 
Since the resolution of the newest NMA CO(1-0) observation is 3.0'' x 2.4'',
 we request the angular resolution beam size of 3'',
 which is similar to the NMA observation.
The noise level of the NMA CO(1-0) channel maps is
 4.9 mJy/beam with velocity resolution of 20.8 km/s,
 which needs 90 hours observation time for NMA with field of view of 2 arcmin.
Therefore,  30% of the NMA noise level is corresponding to
 1.9 mJy/beam with velocity resolution of 20 km/s and angular resolution of 3'' for ALMA.
In order to cover the intense northern X-ray outflow, 
 we set the field center at RA 11:20:16.15 and Dec 13:35:43.6
 with position angle of 30 degree.
We need ACA in order to enhance the wide-field imaging capability.
We optimize the total number of pointings in 12m Array and ACA
 in order to get minimum pointing number but to cover maximum area of the X-ray outflow.
Thus we set the field size of 1.7 arcmin x 1.1 arcmin.
This requires 1.72 hours with 11 pointings for total 12m array time,
 and 6.89 hours with  pointings for total ACA time.
The estimated total time is 8.61 hours.

We set up the rest frequency of CO(1-0) 115.27~GHz with bandwidth of 1875 MHz (velocity resolution of 2.55 km/s) in baseband-1.
In order to subtract the continuum emission from CO(1-0),
 we set up the continuum in baseband-2 with frequency of 113.3962~GHz (=115.27--1.875) with bandwidth of 2~GHz,
 which can reach rms level of 0.3 mJy/beam and is enough for continuum subtraction</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
