    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>The gas mass consumption through galactic outflow plays a key role on galaxies evolution. In order to understand how mass loss affects the galaxies evolution, and it is important to study the outflowing gas through galaxy activities. However, the accurate measurement of losing molecular gas are very rare due to poor sensitivity. Although X-ray detected large-scale ionized outflow with scale of 10-20 kpc, CO emission only detected 0.5-2 kpc molecular outflows. One scenario is that the molecular gas is gravitationally bound in galactic center,  and therefore, the molecular gas can not go outward to further distance.  Another scenario is that the molecular gas can be entrained by ionized outflow, but the sensitivity of past observations is not good enough to detect weak emission.If we could detect molecular gas in the large-scale X-ray outflow area, then the outflowing gas mass will be much more than the current measurement. This indicates that the gas mass loss rate through outflows is faster then the current understanding.  In order to test which scenario is true, we select NGC 3628 to do this study with 1.4 arcmin x 1.9 arcmin mosaic field.</prp:abstract>
